CREATE (:ContentChunk {id: 'fct-module-10-recognize-distortions__chunk_0', parentId: 'fct-module-10-recognize-distortions', chunkIndex: 0, totalChunks: 3, content: '{{{DQUOTE}}introduction{{DQUOTE}}:{{DQUOTE}}C.S.Lewis (Mere Christianity) {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}God can show Himself as He reall is only to real men. And that means not simply t omen who are individually good, but to men who are united together in a body, loving one another, helping one another, show Him to one another. For that is what God ment humanity to be like; like players in one band, or organs in one body. {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nLet’s go back to a concept we explored earlier in the course: seeing ourselves and society itself not as fixed entities, but as processes that are continually changing.  {{BACKSLASH}}nCurrently, information technologies like social media are disproportionately influencing how society is changing. The race to extract human attention ends up distorting people and relationships in a myriad ways.  {{BACKSLASH}}nWe mentioned in Module 4 that social media creates distorted images of its users. These technological infrastructures are not neutral observers but rather poke and prod the user to engage in certain behaviors. But beyond the distorted image of the user from the perspective of the system, it is also true that users have a distorted image of one another.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIn fact, instead of social media being a true mirror and reflection of society, it is better thought of as a “funhouse” mirror. The distortions of ourselves and of others are the psycho-social externalities of the ad-revenue driven, engagement-maximizing business models of these platforms.   {{BACKSLASH}}nHere are some of the most relevant examples of these distortions:{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Engaging Content{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distrotion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Moral Outrage{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Ampification{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Extreme Emotion{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Microtargeting{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Othering{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Disloyalty{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Information Flooding{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Anti-Journalism{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion{{DQUOTE}},{{DQUOTE}}conclusion{{DQUOTE}}:{{DQUOTE}}All these distortions have run rampant in society for over a decade, warping our perception of reality and challenging our ability to discern truth. Under these conditions, the unity of the Body of Christ is severely threatened. Today{{QUOTE}}s dominant social media platforms, rather than supporting the nuanced conversations and diverse viewpoints that Christian community requires, instead carve the population into warring tribes.  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe most engaged and influential voices, including many Christians, often become the most extreme and reactionary, losing sight of Christ{{QUOTE}}s call to be peacemakers (Matthew 5:9). Those who refuse to submit to the social media-augmented culture war are frequently shunned and isolated, ending up confused, angry, and disconnected from community {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- a stark contrast to the biblical vision of unity in diversity (1 Corinthians 12:12-27).  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe integrity of our digital discipleship is at stake. As we{{QUOTE}}ve seen, even our faith can be weaponized against us in the attention economy. The shocking revelation that 19 out of the 20 top Christian Facebook pages were run by foreign click farms should serve as a wake-up call. Our genuine desire for spiritual connection and growth is being exploited, not just undermining our witness but potentially warping our very understanding of Christianity.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIf the church cannot figure out how to create the epistemic commons necessary for the body to be unified under the leadership and direction of Christ as the head, we cannot offer hope to bring truth to the world. We must first take the plank out of our own eye, focusing on how to form disciples and be a truthful and informed people in a post-truth society.  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe Christian community depends on mutual trust and love to function as the Body of Christ. Social media has brought us dangerously close to losing this trust within our church lives. When shared understanding shatters, the witness of the Church is severely compromised.  {{BACKSLASH}}nHowever, as followers of Christ, we are called to be agents of reconciliation in this fragmented world (2 Corinthians 5:18-20). We have a unique opportunity {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- indeed, a responsibility {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- to lead in creating technology that fosters genuine connection and shared understanding. This reflects God{{QUOTE}}s desire for unity among His people and in all of creation, as expressed in Jesus{{QUOTE}} prayer {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}that they may all be one{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} (John 17:21).  {{BACKSLASH}}nAs Christians engaged with technology, we must rise to this challenge. We are called to be {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}wise as serpents and innocent as doves{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} (Matthew 10:16), exercising critical discernment in our digital lives while also working to create spaces that truly reflect the values of our faith. We must reclaim our attention, our platforms, and our very understanding of what it means to be the Church in the digital age.  {{BACKSLASH}}nLet us commit to being at the forefront of developing humane technology {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- technology that honors the imago dei in every user, fosters genuine community, and works towards the unity that Christ desires for His Church. By leveraging our skills and influence, we can create platforms and practices that nurture empathy, promote truthful dialogue, and build bridges across divides.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIn doing so, we embody the reconciling love of Christ in the digital age. This is our call {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- to be {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}salt and light{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} (Matthew 5:13-16) in the digital realm, preserving truth, illuminating paths to genuine understanding, and ultimately pointing towards the reconciliation and shared understanding found in God{{QUOTE}}s coming Kingdom. Only by addressing these challenges within our own communities can we hope to offer a transformative witness to a world in desperate need of truth and unity.{{DQUOTE}},{{DQUOTE}}rawMarkdown{{DQUOTE}}:{{DQUOTE}}{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n## Creating Shared Understanding {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- Recognize Distortions{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Day{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n8.0{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Objective{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n5.0{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Foundations of Humane Tech Concepts Review{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nCreating Shared Understanding Part 1 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- The Breakdown of Shared Understanding{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n1{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}. Impact of Social Media on Shared Understanding  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- How social media shapes perceptions and distorts reality  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- The role of engagement-driven algorithms in creating distortions  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- National security implications of fragmented shared understanding{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n2{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}. Key Distortions in Social Media  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- The {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}engaging content{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- The {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}moral outrage{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- The {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}amplification{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- The {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}extreme emotion{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- The {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}microtargeting{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- The {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}othering{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- The {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}disloyalty{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- The {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}information flooding{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- The {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}anti-journalism{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} distortion{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n3{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}. Consequences of Broken Shared Understanding  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- Challenges to democratic processes  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- Increased polarization and tribalism  {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- Erosion of cultural trust necessary for effective governance{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Size{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n31.0{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Foundations of Christians and Technology Learning Objectives{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nRecognize and articulate how social media and digital technologies are shaping perceptions and potentially distorting reality within Christian communities and the broader society.  {{BACKSLASH}}nAnalyze the role of engagement-driven algorithms in creating distortions and relate this to biblical concepts of truth-seeking and discernment.  {{BACKSLASH}}nEvaluate the national security implications of fragmented shared understanding from a Christian perspective of peace-making and social responsibility.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIdentify and explain the key distortions in social media (e.g., {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}engaging content,{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}moral outrage,{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}amplification,{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} etc.) and relate them to relevant biblical teachings on communication, community, and love.  {{BACKSLASH}}nExamine how these distortions may be affecting Christian discourse, both within churches and in the broader public sphere.  {{BACKSLASH}}nAssess the impact of social media distortions on the church{{QUOTE}}s mission to be a unified body of Christ and its witness to the world.  {{BACKSLASH}}nReflect on personal experiences with these distortions and consider how they align or conflict with one{{QUOTE}}s Christian values and practices.  {{BACKSLASH}}nAnalyze the challenges these distortions pose to democratic processes from a Christian ethical standpoint.  {{BACKSLASH}}nExplore the biblical concept of unity in diversity and how it relates to the increased polarization and tribalism seen in digital spaces.  {{BACKSLASH}}nDiscuss the erosion of cultural trust in light of Christian teachings on community, truthfulness, and bearing false witness.  {{BACKSLASH}}nDevelop a theologically grounded critique of how current digital platforms may be undermining shared understanding within and beyond Christian communities.  {{BACKSLASH}}nPropose ways that Christians can be {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}salt and light{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} in digital spaces, fostering environments of trust, understanding, and reconciliation.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nThese learning objectives aim to help Christian students understand the technological and social dynamics at play while also encouraging them to engage with these issues from a faith-based perspective. The goal is to equip them to be discerning users of technology and potentially to become creators of more humane digital environments that better align with Christian values.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Introduction{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nC.S.Lewis (Mere Christianity) {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}God can show Himself as He reall is only to real men. And that means not simply t omen who are individually good, but to men who are united together in a body, loving one another, helping one another, show Him to one another. For that is what God ment humanity to be like; like players in one band, or organs in one body. {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nLet’s go back to a concept we explored earlier in the course: seeing ourselves and society itself not as fixed entities, but as processes that are continually changing.  {{BACKSLASH}}nCurrently, information technologies like social media are disproportionately influencing how society is changing. The race to extract human attention ends up distorting people and relationships in a myriad ways.  {{BACKSLASH}}nWe mentioned in Module 4 that social media creates distorted images of its users. These technological infrastructures are not neutral observers but rather poke and prod the user to engage in certain behaviors. But beyond the distorted image of the user from the perspective of the system, it is also true that users have a distorted image of one another.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIn fact, instead of social media being a true mirror and reflection of society, it is better thought of as a “funhouse” mirror. The distortions of ourselves and of others are the psycho-social externalities of the ad-revenue driven, engagement-maximizing business models of these platforms.   {{BACKSLASH}}nHere are some of the most relevant examples of these distortions:{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Engaging Content{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distrotion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Moral Outrage{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Ampification{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Extreme Emotion{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Microtargeting{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Othering{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Disloyalty{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Information Flooding{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Anti-Journalism{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} Distortion{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Bible Reference(s){{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nChristian Unity & Harmony has a dependency of Christian Humility {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nGod and Jesus rejoicing in the truth:{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nJohn 14:6 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Jesus said to him, {{QUOTE}}I am the way, and the truth, and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me.{{QUOTE}}{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}  {{BACKSLASH}}n1 Corinthians 13:6 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Love does not rejoice at wrongdoing, but rejoices with the truth.{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}  {{BACKSLASH}}n3 John 1:4 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}I have no greater joy than to hear that my children are walking in the truth.{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nResponsibility to not bear false witness:{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nExodus 20:16 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}You shall not bear false witness against your neighbor.{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} (One of the Ten Commandments)  {{BACKSLASH}}nProverbs 12:22 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Lying lips are an abomination to the Lord, but those who act faithfully are his delight.{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}  {{BACKSLASH}}nColossians 3:9-10 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Do not lie to one another, seeing that you have put off the old self with its practices and have put on the new self, which is being renewed in knowledge after the image of its creator.{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nDangers of lies, slander, and misrepresentation:{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nProverbs 6:16-19 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}There are six things that the Lord hates, seven that are an abomination to him: haughty eyes, a lying tongue, and hands that shed innocent blood, a heart that devises wicked plans, feet that make haste to run to evil, a false witness who breathes out lies, and one who s'});
CREATE (:ContentChunk {id: 'fct-module-10-recognize-distortions__chunk_1', parentId: 'fct-module-10-recognize-distortions', chunkIndex: 1, totalChunks: 3, content: 'ows discord among brothers.{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}  {{BACKSLASH}}nPsalm 101:5 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Whoever slanders his neighbor secretly I will destroy. Whoever has a haughty look and an arrogant heart I will not endure.{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}  {{BACKSLASH}}nJames 3:5-6 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}So also the tongue is a small member, yet it boasts of great things. How great a forest is set ablaze by such a small fire{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}! And the tongue is a fire, a world of unrighteousness.{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}  {{BACKSLASH}}nProverbs 26:28 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}A lying tongue hates its victims, and a flattering mouth works ruin.{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}  {{BACKSLASH}}nEphesians 4:25 {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Therefore, having put away falsehood, let each one of you speak the truth with his neighbor, for we are members one of another.{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nThese verses underscore the importance of truth, the joy found in truthfulness, and the serious spiritual and social consequences of falsehood, which are highly relevant to our current digital information landscape.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Story {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nImagine a bustling digital marketplace of faith. Millions of Christians gather daily, seeking inspiration, connection, and spiritual nourishment. They share prayers, verses, and testimonies. They debate theology and celebrate miracles. This vibrant online community seems to embody the global, interconnected Body of Christ that we{{QUOTE}}ve long envisioned.  {{BACKSLASH}}nBut there{{QUOTE}}s a sobering reality behind this facade.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIn 2019, a shocking investigation revealed that 19 out of the top 20 Christian Facebook pages weren{{QUOTE}}t run by devout believers, earnest ministries, or even well-meaning if misguided prosperity preachers. Instead, these pages – reaching tens of millions of faithful followers – were operated by foreign click farms, primarily based in Kosovo and Macedonia.  {{BACKSLASH}}nLet that sink in. The vast majority of {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}Christian{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} content engaging your family, friends, and fellow church members was created not to edify, but to exploit.  {{BACKSLASH}}nThese click farms recognized a lucrative opportunity in the faith community. They understood that Christians are often trusting, eager to engage with spiritual content, and quick to share messages that resonate with their beliefs. By generating and spreading content that appealed to Christian sensibilities – often with a healthy dose of political outrage – these operators could drive massive engagement, translating into substantial advertising revenue.  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe content itself ranged from benign inspirational quotes (often misattributed) to more insidious misinformation designed to stoke fear and division within the Christian community. Regardless of the specific message, the true purpose was always the same: to capture and monetize the attention of believers.  {{BACKSLASH}}nThis revelation should shake us to our core. As Christians, we{{QUOTE}}re called to be people of truth, integrity, and discernment. Yet here we were, unwittingly promoting and spreading content created by those who saw our faith not as a transformative truth, but as a profitable demographic to be exploited.  {{BACKSLASH}}nMoreover, this situation reveals how our genuine desire for spiritual connection and growth can be weaponized against us in the attention economy. Every share, every comment, every moment spent engaging with this fraudulent content not only lined the pockets of unscrupulous operators but also drowned out authentic Christian voices and ministries trying to make a real impact.  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe implications run deeper still. How many believers have had their understanding of Christianity subtly warped by this steady stream of algorithmically optimized pseudo-faith? How has this distorted the wider world{{QUOTE}}s perception of what Christianity stands for? And how has this contributed to the polarization and tribalism we see both within the Church and in our broader society?  {{BACKSLASH}}nAs followers of Christ, we{{QUOTE}}re called to be {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}wise as serpents and innocent as doves{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} (Matthew 10:16). This situation demands that we reclaim that wisdom, exercising critical discernment in our digital lives. We must recognize that our attention – our most precious resource – is being systematically extracted and exploited, often at the expense of our spiritual well-being and our witness to the world.  {{BACKSLASH}}nThis is not just about being more careful on social media. This is a call to radically reevaluate our relationship with digital platforms and to take an active role in shaping a more authentic, more humane online ecosystem. It{{QUOTE}}s a challenge to create and cultivate digital spaces that truly reflect the values of our faith – spaces that prioritize truth, foster genuine community, and point towards Christ rather than clickbait.  {{BACKSLASH}}nAs we confront this reality, let{{QUOTE}}s allow our righteous anger to fuel positive action. Let{{QUOTE}}s commit to being more discerning consumers and more responsible sharers of content. Let{{QUOTE}}s support authentic Christian voices and ministries in the digital space. And for those of us with the skills and influence to do so, let{{QUOTE}}s lead the charge in creating technology that serves the genuine needs of the faith community rather than exploiting them.  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe integrity of our digital discipleship and the authenticity of our online witness hang in the balance. It{{QUOTE}}s time to reclaim our attention, our platforms, and our very understanding of what it means to be the Church in the digital age.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Discussion Question or Activity{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nThink of church {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}experiences{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} you have worked on, supported, or participated in. Where might they have contributed to or amplified any of these distortions?{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nWhat design features can increase or combat distortion in our shared understanding?{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nHow have I contributed to or been affected by the breakdown of shared understanding?  {{BACKSLASH}}nWhat steps can I take to foster greater understanding in my digital interactions?{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nHow can our church/Christian community better leverage technology to create shared understanding?  {{BACKSLASH}}nWhat principles should guide our use of social media and other digital platforms?{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Conclusion{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nAll these distortions have run rampant in society for over a decade, warping our perception of reality and challenging our ability to discern truth. Under these conditions, the unity of the Body of Christ is severely threatened. Today{{QUOTE}}s dominant social media platforms, rather than supporting the nuanced conversations and diverse viewpoints that Christian community requires, instead carve the population into warring tribes.  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe most engaged and influential voices, including many Christians, often become the most extreme and reactionary, losing sight of Christ{{QUOTE}}s call to be peacemakers (Matthew 5:9). Those who refuse to submit to the social media-augmented culture war are frequently shunned and isolated, ending up confused, angry, and disconnected from community {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- a stark contrast to the biblical vision of unity in diversity (1 Corinthians 12:12-27).  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe integrity of our digital discipleship is at stake. As we{{QUOTE}}ve seen, even our faith can be weaponized against us in the attention economy. The shocking revelation that 19 out of the 20 top Christian Facebook pages were run by foreign click farms should serve as a wake-up call. Our genuine desire for spiritual connection and growth is being exploited, not just undermining our witness but potentially warping our very understanding of Christianity.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIf the church cannot figure out how to create the epistemic commons necessary for the body to be unified under the leadership and direction of Christ as the head, we cannot offer hope to bring truth to the world. We must first take the plank out of our own eye, focusing on how to form disciples and be a truthful and informed people in a post-truth society.  {{BACKSLASH}}nThe Christian community depends on mutual trust and love to function as the Body of Christ. Social media has brought us dangerously close to losing this trust within our church lives. When shared understanding shatters, the witness of the Church is severely compromised.  {{BACKSLASH}}nHowever, as followers of Christ, we are called to be agents of reconciliation in this fragmented world (2 Corinthians 5:18-20). We have a unique opportunity {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- indeed, a responsibility {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- to lead in creating technology that fosters genuine connection and shared understanding. This reflects God{{QUOTE}}s desire for unity among His people and in all of creation, as expressed in Jesus{{QUOTE}} prayer {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}that they may all be one{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} (John 17:21).  {{BACKSLASH}}nAs Christians engaged with technology, we must rise to this challenge. We are called to be {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}wise as serpents and innocent as doves{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} (Matthew 10:16), exercising critical discernment in our digital lives while also working to create spaces that truly reflect the values of our faith. We must reclaim our attention, our platforms, and our very understanding of what it means to be the Church in the digital age.  {{BACKSLASH}}nLet us commit to being at the forefront of developing humane technology {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- technology that honors the imago dei in every user, fosters genuine community, and works towards the unity that Christ desires for His Church. By leveraging our skills and influence, we can create platforms and practices that nurture empathy, promote truthful dialogue, and build bridges across divides.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIn doing so, we embody the reconciling love of Christ in the digital age. This is our call {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}- to be {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}salt and light{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} (Matthew 5:13-16) in the digital realm, preserving truth, illuminating paths to genuine understanding, and ultimately pointing towards the reconciliation and shared understanding found in God{{QUOTE}}s coming Kingdom. Only by addressing these challenges within our own communities can we hope to offer a transformative witness to a world in desperate need of truth and unity.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Application {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nPart 1: Defending Against Distortions and Practicing Social Media Hygiene{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nDigital Literacy Training: Commit to ongoing education in digital literacy, including fact-checking techniques, understanding algorithmic bias, and recognizing misinformation.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIntentional Media Diet: Curate a balanced {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}media diet{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} that includes reputable local news sources, diverse perspectives, and fact-based reporting. Limit exposure to potentially distorting content.  {{BACKSLASH}}nSocial Media Mindfulness: Practice intentional and limited use of social media. Set specific times for usage and stick to them. Use tools to limit notifications and screen time.  {{BACKSLASH}}nContent Verification Habit: Before sharing any content, verify its accuracy using multiple reputable sources. Encourage this practice within your social circles.  {{BACKSLASH}}nEcho Chamber Awareness: Actively seek out perspectives that differ from your own to avoid being trapped in an ideological bubble.  {{BACKSLASH}}nEmotional Checking: Before engaging with or sharing content, pause to consider your emotional state. Are you reacting out of anger, fear, or other strong emotions?  {{BACKSLASH}}nPlatform Knowledge: Understand how different social media platforms work, including their algorithms and content moderation policies. Use this knowledge to navigate them more wisely.  {{BACKSLASH}}nRegular Digital Fasting: Implement regular periods of abstention from social media and digital devices to recalibrate attention and priorities.  {{BACKSLASH}}nPrivacy Protection: Learn about and implement strong privacy practices to limit the amount of personal data available for exploitation.  {{BACKSLASH}}nMindful Engagement: When participating in online discussions, strive to be a voice of reason, empathy, and truth. Model the behavior you wish to see in digital spaces.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Class Homework{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nReclaiming Your Sacred Attention on Social Media  {{BACKSLASH}}nObjective: Reshape your social media environment to prioritize truth and meaningful connections.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nAudit Your Feed (15 minutes):  {{BACKSLASH}}nReview your social media feeds.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIdentify accounts that:  {{BACKSLASH}}na) Trigger strong emotional reactions  {{BACKSLASH}}nb) Seem designed primarily for engagement  {{BACKSLASH}}nc) Might be spreading misinformation{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nThe Great Unfollow (15 minutes):  {{BACKSLASH}}nUnfollow or mute at least 5 problematic accounts.  {{BACKSLASH}}nBriefly note why for each.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nMindful Following (15 minutes):  {{BACKSLASH}}nResearch and follow at least 5 reputable organizations or experts related to your interests.  {{BACKSLASH}}nNote why each new follow will positively contribute to your understanding.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nRebui'});
CREATE (:ContentChunk {id: 'fct-module-10-recognize-distortions__chunk_2', parentId: 'fct-module-10-recognize-distortions', chunkIndex: 2, totalChunks: 3, content: 'lding Bridges (15 minutes):  {{BACKSLASH}}nReflect on any friends or family you{{QUOTE}}ve blocked or muted due to disagreements.  {{BACKSLASH}}nPrayerfully consider unblocking them. Remember, we{{QUOTE}}re called to unity in the body of Christ.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIf you choose to reconnect, plan how to engage more constructively moving forward.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nReflection (15 minutes):  {{BACKSLASH}}nWrite a brief reflection (150-200 words) addressing:  {{BACKSLASH}}nHow this exercise changed your perspective on social media use.  {{BACKSLASH}}nAny challenges you anticipate in maintaining a healthier feed.  {{BACKSLASH}}nYour thoughts on balancing diverse viewpoints with truthful information.  {{BACKSLASH}}nIf applicable, your experience or decision regarding rebuilding connections.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nOne Week Follow-Up:  {{BACKSLASH}}nAfter a week, spend 10 minutes reviewing your adjusted feeds. Note any differences in your social media experience or sense of being informed.  {{BACKSLASH}}nRemember: This exercise is about intentional attention and fostering genuine connections, not isolating yourself from diverse viewpoints.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n### Other Media / Go Deeper / Class Maps{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nHans Rosling: The good news of the decade? Hans Rosling reframes 10 years of UN data with his spectacular visuals, lighting up an astonishing {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}-- mostly unreported {{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}-- piece of front-page-worthy good news. Along the way, he debunks one flawed approach to stats that blots out such vital stories.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nWealth Inequality in America Infographics on the distribution of wealth in America, highlighting both the inequality and the difference between our perception of inequality and the actual numbers. The reality is often not what we think it is.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nHow economic inequality harms societies | Richard Wilkinson We feel instinctively that societies with huge income gaps are somehow going wrong. Richard Wilkinson charts the hard data on economic inequality, and shows what gets worse when rich and poor are too far apart: real effects on health, lifespan, even such basic values as trust.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nExplained | Racial Wealth Gap | FULL EPISODE | Netflix how slavery, housing discrimination and centuries of inequality have compounded to create a racial wealth gap.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nNewscasters Agree: A Christmas Present Or Two Or Ten Edition | CONAN on TBS  Local news people agree: it{{QUOTE}}s okay to be a little selfish this Christmas. Just admit it{{BACKSLASH}}{{BACKSLASH}}!,  This dark piece of humor highlights, how nationalized local media has become that has been replicated into our local communities without any disclaimer do you really know what{{QUOTE}}s local news, and what{{QUOTE}}s just copy and pasted into your newsfeed?{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nBeware online {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}filter bubbles{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} | Eli Pariser, As web companies strive to tailor their services (including news and search results) to our personal tastes, there{{QUOTE}}s a dangerous unintended consequence: We get trapped in a {{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}}filter bubble{{BACKSLASH}}{{DQUOTE}} and don{{QUOTE}}t get exposed to information that could challenge or broaden our worldview. Eli Pariser argues powerfully that this will ultimately prove to be bad for us and bad for democracy. {{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}nWoman Burned by McDonald{{QUOTE}}s Hot Coffee, Then the News Media | Retro Report | The New York Times In 1992, Stella Liebeck spilled scalding McDonald{{QUOTE}}s coffee in her lap and later sued the company, attracting a flood of negative attention. It turns out there was more to the story.{{BACKSLASH}}n{{BACKSLASH}}n{{DQUOTE}}}'});
