// Chunks for: public-observer-teacher-readme (2 chunks)
CREATE (:ContentChunk {id: 'public-observer-teacher-readme__chunk_0', parentId: 'public-observer-teacher-readme', chunkIndex: 0, totalChunks: 2, content: '---{{NEWLINE}}epic: public_observer{{NEWLINE}}user_type: teacher{{NEWLINE}}archetype_name: {{DQUOTE}}Educational Professional{{DQUOTE}}{{NEWLINE}}epic_domain: {{DQUOTE}}Civic Democracy - Public oversight and democratic participation{{DQUOTE}}{{NEWLINE}}governance_scope: [school, district, municipality, state]{{NEWLINE}}related_users: [parent, board_member, student, politician, community_organizer]{{NEWLINE}}---{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}# Teacher - Public Observer{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}## Archetype{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}The teacher archetype represents educational professionals who possess irreplaceable frontline knowledge about how education policies, budget decisions, and administrative directives actually affect students and learning—yet are systematically excluded from meaningful decision-making roles. They see daily impacts of overcrowded classrooms, inadequate resources, misguided curriculum mandates, and administrative priorities that contradict educational best practices. They know which students are struggling, which families need support, which programs actually work, and which policies sound good in board meetings but create chaos in classrooms. Yet their expertise is routinely ignored by administrators focused on metrics and compliance, board members who{{QUOTE}}ve never taught, and politicians who treat education as political football.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Teachers face profound tension between professional knowledge and institutional constraints. They{{QUOTE}}re expected to educate students effectively while navigating: class sizes that make individualized attention impossible, standardized testing regimes that narrow curriculum, administrative mandates that consume time without improving learning, resource scarcity requiring personal spending on supplies, and evaluation systems that ignore actual teaching complexity. When they speak honestly about these constraints, they risk retaliation from administrators or being dismissed as self-interested complainers. When they stay silent, harmful policies continue unchallenged. Teacher unions provide some collective voice and protection but can be politically constrained or captured by their own bureaucracies.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Public Observers transform teacher civic engagement by creating safe, credible channels for their expertise to inform decision-making. Instead of relying on administrator interpretations of classroom realities or parent perspectives that see only their own children, decision-makers get teacher insights at scale: aggregated anonymously to prevent retaliation, documented systematically to show patterns rather than anecdotes, connected to student outcomes to ground in results rather than just complaints. For individual teachers, Observers provide information about policy decisions affecting their work, facilitate coordination with colleagues and parents around shared concerns, and track whether administrator and board promises to teachers are kept. Teachers stop being policy subjects and become contributors to educational democracy.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}## Core Needs{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Voice Without Retaliation**: Teachers need to share professional insights about education policy and practice without risking employment, negative evaluations, or hostile work environments. When a principal mandates an instructional approach that contradicts research and classroom reality, teachers who speak up may be labeled {{DQUOTE}}difficult{{DQUOTE}} or {{DQUOTE}}resistant to change.{{DQUOTE}} When district cuts support staff, teachers who protest budget priorities may face retaliation. Observers enable teachers to contribute professional knowledge anonymously or aggregated—patterns surface without exposing individuals. A teacher reports through Observer that new curriculum is developmentally inappropriate; 45 other teachers report similar concerns; district leadership sees pattern without knowing who raised issues—policy gets reconsidered without teacher retaliation.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Decision Intelligence and Advocacy Tools**: Teachers need to understand education policy decisions affecting their work and students, and engage effectively in advocacy when needed. School board agenda items use jargon and euphemism ({{DQUOTE}}instructional efficiency optimization{{DQUOTE}} means cutting positions); state education policy operates in bureaucratic obscurity. Teachers have limited time beyond teaching demands to track and decode policy. Observers provide: plain-language summaries of education decisions, impact analysis on teaching and learning, historical context and comparison data, and concrete advocacy pathways. A teacher learns through morning Observer brief that tonight{{QUOTE}}s board meeting will vote on increasing class sizes—can coordinate response with colleagues and parents.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Coalition Building Across Stakeholder Groups**: Teachers need to build effective coalitions with parents, community members, and supportive board members around shared educational interests. But coordination is difficult—teachers can{{QUOTE}}t easily communicate with parents en masse, don{{QUOTE}}t know which community members care about education issues, and struggle to identify genuine board allies. Observers facilitate coalition building by: identifying shared concerns across teachers and parents (both worry about class sizes), connecting teachers with organized parent groups and community advocates, surfacing board member voting patterns to identify allies, and enabling secure coordination without administrator surveillance. Teachers, parents, and community organizers coordinate through Observer platform to advocate for school funding—much more powerful coalition than teachers alone.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Evidence-Based Professional Advocacy**: Teachers need compelling evidence to support professional judgments about education policy and practice. When teachers say {{DQUOTE}}class sizes matter,{{DQUOTE}} administrators cite studies claiming otherwise; when teachers advocate for resources, boards claim budget constraints. Observers provide teachers with: data on classroom conditions across schools (documenting disparities and trends), research evidence on educational practices and policies, outcome tracking showing student impacts of policies, and comparison data from other districts and states. A teacher advocates for lower class sizes using Observer data: student outcomes decline as class sizes increase in our own district, research shows class size effects, neighboring district has better ratios and better results—advocacy is evidence-based rather than just professional opinion.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Working Conditions Transparency**: Teachers need visibility into how their working conditions compare across schools, districts, and states—both to understand whether their struggles are unique or systemic and to advocate for improvements. One teacher experiencing impossible workload doesn{{QUOTE}}t know if it{{QUOTE}}s their school or widespread; one school with outdated materials doesn{{QUOTE}}t know if neighboring schools are better resourced. Observers document working conditions: class sizes, resources, support staff, planning time, professional development, evaluation burdens, and compare across contexts. Teachers discover whether problems are local (requiring school/district advocacy) or systemic (requiring union and political action), and can advocate with evidence of disparities and best practices.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}## Key Relationships{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**To Parents**: Teachers and parents share fundamental alignment—both deeply invested in children{{QUOTE}}s education and wellbeing. But traditional systems create distance and sometimes conflict between them. Parents see only their child{{QUOTE}}s experience; teachers see patterns across many students but can{{QUOTE}}t easily communicate systemically. Parents may blame teachers for problems caused by administrative decisions (overcrowded classes, inadequate resources). Observers bridge this gap by: making systemic education issues visible to parents (not just their child{{QUOTE}}s struggles but patterns), surfacing teacher professional insights about policy impacts, facilitating teacher-parent coalition building around shared interests, and distinguishing between teacher effectiveness and structural constraints. When budget cuts increase class sizes, Observers help parents understand it{{QUOTE}}s not their child{{QUOTE}}s teacher choosing to provide less attention—it{{QUOTE}}s a policy decision teacher and parent can jointly oppose.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**To Board Members**: Teachers are the frontline professionals that boards govern—but boards often hear from administrators about teacher perspectives rather than teachers themselves. Board members may view teachers as self-interested employees rather than education experts; teachers may view boards as out-of-touch or captured by administrators. Observers improve this relationship by: providing boards with aggregated teacher insights on policy impacts, surfacing teacher expertise to inform board decisions, making board decisions visible to teachers early enough to provide input, and tracking whether board promises to improve teaching conditions are kept. A board member sees Observer data on teacher concerns about curriculum mandate, seeks teacher input before voting, makes better-informed decision.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**To Politicians**: Teachers engage with politicians as education advocates and constituents. State legislators set education funding, policy, and standards; municipal politicians control school budgets; all respond to constituent pressure. Teachers are organized through unions but individual teacher voices and professional expertise can be powerful. Observers help teachers engage politically by: making education policy decisions visible across state/local levels, connecting teacher professional insights to political advocacy, facilitating teacher-constituent coalitions (teachers + parents + community = political power), and tracking politician education votes and commitments. A state legislator sees Observer-facilitated campaign from teachers and parents about education funding crisis, champions funding increase.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**To Students**: Teachers{{QUOTE}} primary professional relationship is with students—teaching, supporting, advocating for them. But in civic democracy contexts, students (especially older students) are also stakeholders whose voices matter. Observers help teachers amplify student perspectives by: documenting student experiences and outcomes, connecting student voices to education policy decisions, and helping teachers advocate based on student needs rather than just professional interests. A teacher advocates for arts programs using Observer data on student engagement and outcomes, centers student voices in advocacy.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**To Administrators**: Teachers work under administrative direction—principals, district administrators, state education bureaucrats set policies and priorities that teachers implement. This can be collaborative (administrators and teachers working together for student success) or antagonistic (administrators imposing mandates that teachers know won{{QUOTE}}t work). Observers affect this relationship by: making administrator decisions and rationales visible to teachers, providing teachers with evidence to question harmful mandates, tracking administrator promises and follow-through, and surfacing when administrator priorities diverge from teaching and learning needs. This can improve education decision-making but may also surface conflicts between professional judgment and bureaucratic priorities.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**To Community Organizers**: Teachers are natural allies for education justice organizers working on school equity, funding, and reform. Teachers have professional expertise and frontline knowledge; organizers have community relationships and campaign capacity. Observers facilitate teacher-organizer collaboration by: connecting teachers concerned about issues to organizing campaigns, providing research and evidence for campaigns, surfacing teacher insights to ground organizing in classroom realities, and enabling teachers to participate in organizing without job risk. An education equity organizer recruits teachers (anonymously through Observer platform) to provide testimony about resource disparities, builds powerful campaign combining teacher expertise and community voice.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}'});
CREATE (:ContentChunk {id: 'public-observer-teacher-readme__chunk_1', parentId: 'public-observer-teacher-readme', chunkIndex: 1, totalChunks: 2, content: '**With Elohim Agents**:{{NEWLINE}}- **Public_observer agent**: Provides school board and education policy monitoring, surfaces decisions affecting teachers and students, facilitates teacher input and coordination{{NEWLINE}}- **Education_elohim agent**: Offers specialized education research and policy analysis, cross-district and cross-state comparison, evidence-based practice guidance{{NEWLINE}}- **Classroom_elohim agent**: Documents classroom conditions and teaching realities (aggregated and anonymized), tracks student outcomes, surfaces teacher professional insights{{NEWLINE}}- **Union_elohim agent**: Coordinates with teacher unions for collective advocacy while preserving individual teacher voice, tracks contract negotiations and working conditions{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}## Relevant Governance Layers{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}### Geographic/Political{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**School Layer**{{NEWLINE}}Individual schools are where teaching happens—school site councils, principal decisions, departmental policies affect daily teaching and learning. Teachers need voice in school-level decisions about: instructional approaches, resource allocation, scheduling, discipline policies, school culture. Observers help by: documenting school conditions and needs, facilitating teacher input in school decisions, comparing school conditions across district, and surfacing teacher concerns to school leadership. A school{{QUOTE}}s teachers use Observer to document lack of support staff, advocate collectively for resources, demonstrate need to principal and district.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**District Layer**{{NEWLINE}}School district governance—board, superintendent, central administration—sets policies, allocates resources, and creates conditions for all schools. District decisions about budget priorities, curriculum mandates, evaluation systems, class size policies profoundly affect teaching. Teachers need district governance to respect professional expertise and create conditions for effective teaching. Observers help teachers engage district governance by: monitoring school board meetings and decisions, providing evidence for teacher advocacy on district policies, facilitating teacher-parent-community coalitions around district priorities, and tracking district implementation of policies. A district{{QUOTE}}s teachers coordinate through Observer to advocate for smaller class sizes at board meeting, present evidence of learning impacts, align with parent concerns—board reprioritizes budget.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**State Layer**{{NEWLINE}}State legislatures and education departments set funding formulas, curriculum standards, testing requirements, teacher evaluation systems, and education regulations. State policy profoundly affects classroom teaching but operates distantly from classroom realities. Teachers need state policy informed by professional expertise rather than just political considerations. Observers help teachers engage state policy by: tracking state education legislation and rulemaking, analyzing state policy impacts on teaching and learning, facilitating statewide teacher advocacy coordination, connecting teacher expertise to political processes, and enabling teacher-parent coalition building at state scale. State teachers use Observer to coordinate testimony about testing mandates harming learning, build coalition with parents, pressure legislators to reform—reduces testing burden.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}### Functional{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Educational Layer**{{NEWLINE}}This is teachers{{QUOTE}} primary domain—education policy, curriculum, instruction, student support, school resources and conditions. Teachers are professionals with expertise about teaching and learning who should be central voices in education decisions but are often marginalized. Observers strengthen teacher voice in education governance by: surfacing teacher professional insights to decision-makers, providing teachers with evidence for advocacy, facilitating teacher collaboration and coordination, tracking education outcomes to ground policy in results, and connecting teacher expertise to parent and community concerns. Teachers stop being policy subjects and become contributors to educational democracy.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Ecological Layer**{{NEWLINE}}School environmental conditions affect teaching and learning—air quality, green space, environmental health, climate impacts. Teachers see how environmental factors affect student health, concentration, attendance. They can be powerful advocates for environmental justice in schools. Observers help by: documenting school environmental conditions and disparities (which schools have AC, green space, toxic exposure), connecting environmental factors to student outcomes, facilitating teacher advocacy for environmental improvements, and building coalitions with environmental justice advocates. Teachers use Observer data on school environmental conditions to advocate for climate adaptation investments in under-resourced schools.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Workplace Layer**{{NEWLINE}}Teachers are workers with labor interests—wages, benefits, working conditions, job security, professional respect. Teacher unions advocate for labor interests collectively. Observers help teachers and unions by: documenting working conditions across schools and districts, tracking contract negotiations and implementation, comparing teacher compensation and conditions across jurisdictions, and facilitating teacher collective action. Teachers use Observer to document unpaid overtime, lack of planning time, resource inadequacy—strengthens union contract negotiations for better working conditions.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}## Implementation Notes{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Technical**:{{NEWLINE}}  - Teacher dashboard showing: upcoming education decisions affecting teaching and students, school/district/state education news, professional collaboration opportunities, advocacy actions{{NEWLINE}}  - Anonymous reporting system: teachers can share professional insights about classroom conditions, policy impacts, student needs without revealing identity{{NEWLINE}}  - Aggregated pattern detection: individual anonymous reports aggregate into patterns that inform decision-making without exposing reporters{{NEWLINE}}  - Cross-school/district comparison: teachers can see how working conditions, resources, policies compare across contexts{{NEWLINE}}  - Research integration: connecting teacher questions and concerns to education research evidence{{NEWLINE}}  - Professional learning community support: facilitating teacher collaboration and expertise sharing{{NEWLINE}}  - Advocacy tools: evidence packages for testimony, coalition coordination, policy impact analysis{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Privacy**:{{NEWLINE}}  - Teachers face employment retaliation for honest professional assessment of administrator decisions, policy impacts, school conditions{{NEWLINE}}  - Anonymous contribution essential: teachers can report classroom realities, policy impacts, student needs without administrator knowing who{{NEWLINE}}  - Aggregated reporting protects individuals while surfacing patterns: {{DQUOTE}}45 teachers report this curriculum is developmentally inappropriate{{DQUOTE}} without identifying the 45{{NEWLINE}}  - Pseudonymous advocacy: teachers can participate in campaigns without public exposure unless they choose{{NEWLINE}}  - Protection from administrator surveillance of teacher communications and coordination{{NEWLINE}}  - Distinction between teacher professional insights (legitimately anonymous) and public employee political activity (appropriately public){{NEWLINE}}  - Clear data governance: teacher contributions used only for education improvement, never sold or exploited{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Interface**:{{NEWLINE}}  - Mobile-first: teachers engage during brief moments—planning periods, commutes, after students leave{{NEWLINE}}  - Quick contribution: {{DQUOTE}}Report a concern{{DQUOTE}} in under 60 seconds—teachers don{{QUOTE}}t have time for lengthy processes{{NEWLINE}}  - Professional community features: connect with colleagues across schools, share practices and insights, coordinate advocacy{{NEWLINE}}  - Evidence and research access: teachers need credible sources for professional advocacy, not just opinion{{NEWLINE}}  - Student-centered framing: emphasizing student wellbeing and learning rather than just teacher interests—though often aligned{{NEWLINE}}  - Integration with existing teacher platforms: union communications, professional development systems, learning management systems{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Democratic Health**:{{NEWLINE}}  - Teachers strengthen educational democracy by contributing irreplaceable professional expertise about teaching and learning to policy decisions—Observers make this contribution possible at scale without individual risk{{NEWLINE}}  - Failure modes to avoid: Enabling teacher complaints without constructive contribution, facilitating teacher resistance to necessary accountability, replacing administrator decision-making with teacher preference without considering other stakeholders (parents, students, community), creating teacher-administrator antagonism rather than professional collaboration{{NEWLINE}}  - Success metrics: Teacher professional expertise informing education policy decisions, improved teaching and learning conditions, student outcomes improving as policy respects classroom realities, teacher satisfaction and retention improving{{NEWLINE}}  - Balance teacher interests as workers with professional responsibilities to students: sometimes these align (better working conditions = better learning), sometimes tension exists (teacher seniority versus student needs)—Observers should serve student-centered education while respecting teacher professionalism{{NEWLINE}}  - Key principle: Observers amplify teacher professional voice in education decision-making, they don{{QUOTE}}t replace democratic governance or administrator leadership—teachers are essential stakeholders, not sole decision-makers{{NEWLINE}}'});
