CREATE (:ContentChunk {id: 'value-scanner-young-child-scenarios-family__chunk_0', parentId: 'value-scanner-young-child-scenarios-family', chunkIndex: 0, totalChunks: 2, content: '---{{NEWLINE}}epic: value_scanner{{NEWLINE}}user_type: young_child{{NEWLINE}}governance_layer: family{{NEWLINE}}scene: morning_routine_participation{{NEWLINE}}related_users: [parent, child, partner]{{NEWLINE}}related_layers: [individual, neighborhood]{{NEWLINE}}interacts_with: [personal_agent, family_elohim]{{NEWLINE}}---{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}# Family Layer Scenario - Young Child{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}## Context{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Wednesday morning, 7:15 AM. Six-year-old Emma wakes up to her personal_agent{{QUOTE}}s gentle alarm—a song she chose yesterday. Today feels different though. On her kid-sized tablet, a special message appears:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**🌟 Good morning, Emma! Today is a family teamwork day. Want to see your mission?**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma, still sleepy but curious, taps yes.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Emma{{QUOTE}}s Family Mission:**{{NEWLINE}}1. 🐱 Feed the cats (you can do this!){{NEWLINE}}2. 📚 Find your library books (they{{QUOTE}}re due today!){{NEWLINE}}3. 👗 Choose school clothes (remember: comfy clothes on school days!){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}This isn{{QUOTE}}t a parent nagging her. This is family_elohim coordinating the Parker household{{QUOTE}}s morning, and Emma is a real participant—not just a child being managed, but a family member contributing to collective success.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}This is the **family layer** for a young child: where she learns she{{QUOTE}}s part of something bigger than herself, where family values shape her choices, and where her contributions actually matter.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}## The Story{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**7:20 AM - Emma{{QUOTE}}s First Mission: Feed the Cats**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma pads downstairs in her pajamas. The cats, Pepper and Sage, are already meowing. Her tablet shows a simple checklist:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Feeding Pepper and Sage:**{{NEWLINE}}- ✓ Use the measuring cup (1 scoop each){{NEWLINE}}- ✓ Fill water bowls{{NEWLINE}}- ✓ Tell family_elohim when done!{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma has done this before, but today she notices something: when she finishes, her tablet shows not just a gold star for her, but something new:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Parker Family Progress:**{{NEWLINE}}- Emma: Cats fed! ✓{{NEWLINE}}- Tommy: Making breakfast! ✓{{NEWLINE}}- Mom: Getting ready for work...{{NEWLINE}}- Dad: Packing lunches...{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma realizes: **Everyone has jobs. Everyone is helping.** She{{QUOTE}}s not just being good—she{{QUOTE}}s part of the family{{QUOTE}}s morning success.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**7:30 AM - Emma{{QUOTE}}s Second Mission: Library Books**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma{{QUOTE}}s tablet vibrates gently: *{{DQUOTE}}Next mission: Find your library books. They{{QUOTE}}re due today! Where did you leave them?{{DQUOTE}}*{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma thinks. She remembers reading in the living room yesterday. She runs to check—yes! Two books under the couch cushions.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}But when she scans them with her tablet{{QUOTE}}s camera, her personal_agent says:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}*{{DQUOTE}}Good finding! But wait—this book has one more day until it{{QUOTE}}s due. The other one is due today. Want to return both, or keep one more day?{{DQUOTE}}*{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}This is a teaching moment. Emma could return both (easier for Mom), or keep one (she{{QUOTE}}s not done reading it).{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}She chooses: **Return the due one, keep the other one day.**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Her agent responds: *{{DQUOTE}}Smart thinking! You{{QUOTE}}re following the family rule: {{QUOTE}}Return library books on time.{{QUOTE}} And you{{QUOTE}}re also thinking about what YOU need. Mom will be proud.{{DQUOTE}}*{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Family values (return things on time) + Individual needs (Emma{{QUOTE}}s reading) = Balanced decision.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**7:40 AM - Emma{{QUOTE}}s Third Mission: The Clothes Choice**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma opens her closet. She immediately reaches for her princess dress—the sparkly one she loves.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}But her tablet gently reminds her:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}*{{DQUOTE}}Today is a school day. Remember our family rule?{{DQUOTE}}*{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma pouts. She WANTS to wear the princess dress. Her tablet shows two choices:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**What do you want to do?**{{NEWLINE}}1. 👗 Wear comfy clothes today (family rule), princess dress this weekend{{NEWLINE}}2. 😢 Tell Mom you really want to wear the dress today{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma thinks. She really, really wants the dress. She taps option 2.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Her tablet responds: *{{DQUOTE}}Okay! I{{QUOTE}}ll tell Mom you have strong feelings about this. She{{QUOTE}}s the family rule-keeper. Let{{QUOTE}}s see what she says.{{DQUOTE}}*{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**The Family Governance Moment:**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Downstairs, Sarah{{QUOTE}}s phone buzzes: *{{DQUOTE}}Emma really wants to wear her princess dress today. Family rule says school days = comfy clothes. Do you want to:*{{NEWLINE}}1. *Stick to the family rule (teach consistency)*{{NEWLINE}}2. *Make an exception today (acknowledge Emma{{QUOTE}}s feelings)*{{NEWLINE}}3. *Talk with Emma about why the rule exists{{DQUOTE}}*{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Sarah chooses option 3. She comes upstairs and kneels next to Emma.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}{{DQUOTE}}I see you really love that dress,{{DQUOTE}} Sarah says gently. {{DQUOTE}}Can you tell me why you want to wear it today?{{DQUOTE}}{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma: {{DQUOTE}}Because it makes me feel pretty and special.{{DQUOTE}}{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Sarah: {{DQUOTE}}You ARE special. Every day. You know what? On Friday, we can have {{QUOTE}}special dress day{{QUOTE}} where everyone wears something fancy. Would that work?{{DQUOTE}}{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma thinks. Friday is two days away. But the idea of EVERYONE wearing fancy clothes sounds fun. She nods.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Sarah: {{DQUOTE}}So today, comfy clothes. Friday, princess dress. Deal?{{DQUOTE}}{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma: {{DQUOTE}}Deal. But can I wear my sparkly shoes today?{{DQUOTE}}{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Sarah laughs. {{DQUOTE}}Sparkly shoes are definitely comfy-clothes approved.{{DQUOTE}}{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**What Just Happened (Governance in Action):**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}1. **Family rule was maintained** (school days = comfy clothes){{NEWLINE}}2. **Emma{{QUOTE}}s feelings were acknowledged** (she wanted to feel special){{NEWLINE}}3. **A compromise was negotiated** (sparkly shoes + Friday dress-up day){{NEWLINE}}4. **Emma participated in the decision** (she had voice, not just obedience){{NEWLINE}}5. **Family values were taught, not forced** (Emma understands WHY the rule exists){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}This is family-layer governance for a young child: **boundaries with respect, rules with relationship, authority with love.**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**8:00 AM - Family Morning Celebration**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}The kitchen hub display shows the Parker family{{QUOTE}}s morning achievements:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Parker Family Wednesday Morning:**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**EVERYONE CONTRIBUTED!**{{NEWLINE}}- Emma: 🐱 Fed cats, 📚 Found library books, 👗 Made good clothing choice{{NEWLINE}}- Tommy: 🍳 Made breakfast for Emma and himself{{NEWLINE}}- Mom: 📋 Organized everyone{{QUOTE}}s schedules, 🚗 Ready to drive everyone{{NEWLINE}}- Dad: 🥪 Packed healthy lunches, ☕ Made coffee for Mom{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Family Wins:**{{NEWLINE}}- ✓ No one is late!{{NEWLINE}}- ✓ Cats are happy{{NEWLINE}}- ✓ Library books ready to return{{NEWLINE}}- ✓ Everyone ate breakfast{{NEWLINE}}- ✓ Family worked together{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma sees her name on the display with her contributions. She feels proud. Not because an adult praised her, but because she sees herself as part of a team that succeeded.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Tommy high-fives her. {{DQUOTE}}Good job feeding Pepper and Sage, Emma!{{DQUOTE}}{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma beams. Her care work was seen. Her contribution mattered.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}## Governance Mechanics{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Family Layer for Young Children:**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}At ages 5-7, the family layer is about **learning to be part of a collective** while respecting the child{{QUOTE}}s developing autonomy:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Family Sovereignty Over Child (within constitutional bounds):**{{NEWLINE}}- Parents set family rules (school clothes, bedtime, safety){{NEWLINE}}- Family values apply to all members, including Emma{{NEWLINE}}- Parents have final authority on decisions affecting child{{QUOTE}}s welfare{{NEWLINE}}- But Emma{{QUOTE}}s voice and feelings are heard and considered{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Constitutional Constraints on Family Authority:**{{NEWLINE}}- Cannot violate Emma{{QUOTE}}s fundamental rights (dignity, safety, emotional wellbeing){{NEWLINE}}- Must respect Emma{{QUOTE}}s developmental autonomy (age-appropriate choices){{NEWLINE}}- Cannot use coercion or manipulation (gentle guidance, not force){{NEWLINE}}- Subject to community norms about child welfare{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**How Family Authority Works for Young Child:**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}1. **Family Rules (established by parents, applied consistently):**{{NEWLINE}}   - {{DQUOTE}}Comfy clothes on school days{{DQUOTE}} (practical safety and comfort){{NEWLINE}}   - {{DQUOTE}}Return library books on time{{DQUOTE}} (teaching responsibility){{NEWLINE}}   - {{DQUOTE}}Everyone contributes to family care work{{DQUOTE}} (collective values){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}2. **Emma{{QUOTE}}s Voice Within Family Bounds:**{{NEWLINE}}   - Emma can express desire to break rule (princess dress request){{NEWLINE}}   - Parents listen and negotiate (sparkly shoes compromise){{NEWLINE}}   - Emma{{QUOTE}}s feelings matter, even when rule is maintained{{NEWLINE}}   - She learns: rules have reasons, and she can question respectfully{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}3. **Age-Appropriate Contribution:**{{NEWLINE}}   - Emma CAN feed cats independently (builds competence){{NEWLINE}}   - Emma CANNOT make complex family decisions (developmentally inappropriate){{NEWLINE}}   - Her contributions are real and valued (not busywork){{NEWLINE}}   - She sees herself as family member, not just child being managed{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Subsidiarity for Young Children:**{{NEWLINE}}- Some decisions belong to Emma (what to draw, how to feel){{NEWLINE}}- Some decisions belong to family (clothing rules, safety boundaries){{NEWLINE}}- Some decisions are negotiated (sparkly shoes compromise){{NEWLINE}}- Emma is learning WHERE decisions belong (governance literacy){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}## Protocol Interactions{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Family_elohim Coordinating Young Child:**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}```{{NEWLINE}}family_elohim (Parker household){{NEWLINE}}├── Tracks Emma{{QUOTE}}s capabilities (can feed cats independently){{NEWLINE}}├── Generates age-appropriate missions (simple, achievable){{NEWLINE}}├── Coordinates Emma{{QUOTE}}s contributions with family needs{{NEWLINE}}├── Escalates to parents when Emma needs help or has conflict{{NEWLINE}}└── Celebrates Emma{{QUOTE}}s participation (she{{QUOTE}}s part of family team){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Morning Coordination:{{NEWLINE}}family_elohim identifies family needs:{{NEWLINE}}├── Cats need feeding (Emma can do this){{NEWLINE}}├── Library books due (Emma knows where they are){{NEWLINE}}├── Emma needs to get dressed (requires guidance, family rule){{NEWLINE}}└── Generates Emma{{QUOTE}}s mission list (appropriate to her capacity){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma{{QUOTE}}s personal_agent receives mission from family_elohim:{{NEWLINE}}├── Presents in Emma-friendly format (pictures, simple language){{NEWLINE}}├── Guides Emma through tasks (checklist, encouragement){{NEWLINE}}├── Reports completion back to family_elohim{{NEWLINE}}└── Escalates when Emma faces decision beyond her authority{{NEWLINE}}```{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**The Princess Dress Negotiation:**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}```{{NEWLINE}}7:40 AM - Emma wants princess dress{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma{{QUOTE}}s personal_agent:{{NEWLINE}}├── Detects: Emma{{QUOTE}}s choice conflicts with family rule{{NEWLINE}}├── Presents options: follow rule OR express strong feeling to parent{{NEWLINE}}├── Emma chooses: express feeling{{NEWLINE}}└── personal_agent escalates to family_elohim{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}family_elohim:{{NEWLINE}}├── Recognizes: Family rule conflict requiring parent decision{{NEWLINE}}├── Notifies Sarah (parent) with context and options{{NEWLINE}}├── Sarah chooses: talk with Emma (relationship approach){{NEWLINE}}└── Facilitates conversation (doesn{{QUOTE}}t force decision){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Sarah and Emma negotiate:{{NEWLINE}}├── Sarah acknowledges Emma{{QUOTE}}s feelings (emotional validation){{NEWLINE}}├── Sarah explains rule rationale (teaching, not commanding){{NEWLINE}}├── Together find compromise (sparkly shoes + Friday dress-up){{NEWLINE}}└── Emma accepts voluntarily (not coerced compliance){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Outcome:{{NEWLINE}}├── Family rule maintained (consistency){{NEWLINE}}├── Emma{{QUOTE}}s voice heard (respect){{NEWLINE}}├── Relationship strengthened (connection){{NEWLINE}}└── Emma learns negotiation and governance (civic education){{NEWLINE}}```{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Privacy Within Family:**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}```{{NEWLINE}}What Emma{{QUOTE}}s personal_agent knows (private to Emma):{{NEWLINE}}├── Emma really loves the princess dress (strong preference){{NEWLINE}}├── Emma can follow rules even when disappointed (emotional regulation){{NEWLINE}}├── Emma responds well to explanation + compromise (learning style){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}What family_elohim knows (family-level coordination):{{NEWLINE}}├── Emma completed morning missions (yes){{NEWLINE}}├── Emma needed parent help with clothing decision (appropriate escalation){{NEWLINE}}├── Emma is contributing to family care work (participation tracked){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}What parents can see:{{NEWLINE}}├── Emma{{QUOTE}}s task completion (cats fed, books found){{NEWLINE}}├── Emma{{QUOTE}}s challenges (wanted princess dress, negotiated){{NEWLINE}}├── Emma{{QUOTE}}s care contributions (quantified and celebrated){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}What Emma can keep private:{{NEWLINE}}├── How she felt about the decision (unless she shares){{NEWLINE}}├── What she drew or played after (individual layer){{NEWLINE}}├── Her internal reasoning (developing autonomy){{NEWLINE}}```{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}## Care Made Visible{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**What Was Invisible:**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Before this morning, Emma{{QUOTE}}s family contributions were invisible or taken for granted:{{NEWLINE}}- Feeding cats was {{DQUOTE}}just what Emma does{{DQUOTE}} (not recognized as care work){{NEWLINE}}- Finding library books was {{DQUOTE}}her responsibility{{DQUOTE}} (not seen as helping the family){{NEWLINE}}- Following family rules was {{DQUOTE}}good behavior{{DQUOTE}} (not understood as family governance participation){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**How the Family Layer Makes It Visible:**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}1. **Emma Sees Her Contributions Matter:**{{NEWLINE}}   - Family dashboard shows her work alongside everyone else{{QUOTE}}s{{NEWLINE}}   - Tommy high-fives her (peer recognition){{NEWLINE}}   - She understands: the family succeeded BECAUSE everyone contributed{{NEWLINE}}   - Her care work has value, not just compliance{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}2. **Parents See Emma as Participant:**{{NEWLINE}}   - Not just child to be managed, but family member who contributes{{NEWLINE}}   - Her care work (feeding cats) is quantified and celebrated{{NEWLINE}}   - Her voice in decisions (princess dress) is respected{{NEWLINE}}   - She{{QUOTE}}s capable of more than they might assume{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}'});
CREATE (:ContentChunk {id: 'value-scanner-young-child-scenarios-family__chunk_1', parentId: 'value-scanner-young-child-scenarios-family', chunkIndex: 1, totalChunks: 2, content: '3. **Emma Learns Family Governance:**{{NEWLINE}}   - Rules exist for reasons, not arbitrary adult power{{NEWLINE}}   - She can question rules and be heard (democratic participation){{NEWLINE}}   - Compromise is possible when everyone{{QUOTE}}s needs are considered{{NEWLINE}}   - She has responsibilities AND rights within the family{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**How Visibility Creates Value:**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}1. **Developmental Value:**{{NEWLINE}}   - Emma is learning collective responsibility (family teamwork){{NEWLINE}}   - She{{QUOTE}}s developing voice and negotiation skills (civic capacity){{NEWLINE}}   - She understands that her actions affect others (relational awareness){{NEWLINE}}   - She sees herself as capable and contributing (self-efficacy){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}2. **Relational Value:**{{NEWLINE}}   - Sibling bond with Tommy strengthened (mutual recognition){{NEWLINE}}   - Parent-child relationship deepened (respectful negotiation){{NEWLINE}}   - Family cohesion increased (everyone on the same team){{NEWLINE}}   - Trust built through consistent, respectful governance{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}3. **Educational Value:**{{NEWLINE}}   - Emma is learning governance by experiencing it{{NEWLINE}}   - She understands rules, voice, negotiation, compromise{{NEWLINE}}   - She{{QUOTE}}s preparing for community participation (practice at home){{NEWLINE}}   - Early civic education through family democracy{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Who Benefits:**{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Emma:** Competence, voice, belonging, early civic education{{NEWLINE}}- **Parker family:** Smoother mornings, shared responsibility, stronger relationships{{NEWLINE}}- **Future Emma:** Foundation for civic participation and democratic engagement{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}## Connections{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}### Upward from Individual Layer{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma{{QUOTE}}s individual autonomy informed family participation:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Yesterday (individual):** Emma chose to save strawberries for Tommy{{NEWLINE}}- **Today (family):** Emma is trusted with cat-feeding responsibility{{NEWLINE}}- **Individual capacity → Family contribution:** Her autonomy enables collective success{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}### Upward to Neighborhood Layer (future){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma{{QUOTE}}s family participation prepares for neighborhood engagement:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Today (age 6):** Emma feeds family cats, learns family rules{{NEWLINE}}- **Future (age 8):** Emma might feed neighbor{{QUOTE}}s cats, participate in pet care network{{NEWLINE}}- **Family care work → Neighborhood care network:** Skills transfer across layers{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}### Sideways to Sibling (Tommy){{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Emma and Tommy both contribute at family layer:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Tommy{{QUOTE}}s work:** Makes breakfast (helps everyone, including Emma){{NEWLINE}}- **Emma{{QUOTE}}s work:** Feeds cats (helps family){{NEWLINE}}- **Mutual recognition:** High-five moment (peers celebrating each other{{QUOTE}}s care){{NEWLINE}}- **Sibling solidarity:** Both are family team members, not competing{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}### Downward to Individual Layer{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Family participation doesn{{QUOTE}}t erase individual autonomy:{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}- **Family rule:** Comfy clothes on school days (collective value){{NEWLINE}}- **Individual choice:** Emma chooses WHICH comfy clothes (autonomy){{NEWLINE}}- **Family creates space for individual expression:** Sparkly shoes compromise{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}Family layer **enables** individual flourishing by providing structure, safety, and belonging.{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}---{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**This scenario demonstrates:**{{NEWLINE}}- Family layer as young child{{QUOTE}}s introduction to collective governance{{NEWLINE}}- Age-appropriate participation in family care work{{NEWLINE}}- Family rules taught with respect, not force{{NEWLINE}}- Child voice within family authority structure{{NEWLINE}}- Care work made visible and celebrated for even youngest members{{NEWLINE}}- How family coordination prepares for future civic participation{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**Developmental progression:**{{NEWLINE}}- **Age 6 (Emma):** Family rules, basic contributions, learning voice{{NEWLINE}}- **Age 10 (Tommy):** More complex tasks, neighborhood participation begins{{NEWLINE}}- **Age 14+:** Community engagement, policy awareness, full civic participation{{NEWLINE}}{{NEWLINE}}**The family layer is where democracy is learned first. Emma is becoming a citizen, starting at home.**{{NEWLINE}}'});
